        <HEADING SUBTYPE="2">Note</HEADING>
        <FRONT>
           <P>This author's life has been researched earlier for inclusion in the <TITLE LEVEL="MONOGRAPHIC"><XREF URL="http://digital.lib.sfu.ca/ceww-collection" RESP="KME">Canada's Early Women Writers</XREF></TITLE> project at Simon Fraser University. Information in this entry therefore may not be comprehensive, but has been verified.</P>
           <P>Entry revised by Linnea McNally and Katie Gillespie</P>
        </FRONT>
        <AUTHORSUMMARY>
            <HEADING SUBTYPE="2"><NAME STANDARD="LYDIA AGNES EDWARDS">Lydia Agnes Edwards</NAME> (1848-1939)</HEADING>
           <P>As Lydia Agnes Edwards earned her living as a teacher of French, at the Truro Academy and later privately, it is not surprising that she titled one of her works <TITLE LEVEL="MONOGRAPHIC" REF="http://commons.cwrc.ca/islandora:edcf14c0-46c1-4c5c-a4ff-fc05bb55dd67">Pensées Poétiques</TITLE> (1900). Her writing received two unique honours: her poem, <TITLE LEVEL="ANALYTIC">The First Contingent,</TITLE> was chosen to be given as a keepsake to each soldier returning to Truro, NS, from the South African War, and her compilation, <TITLE LEVEL="MONOGRAPHIC" REF="http://commons.cwrc.ca/islandora:02be3def-d043-4018-92b9-d8564a430c67">How Canadians Mourned for Their Queen</TITLE> (1901) received acknowledgement and thanks from King Edward VII and each member of the royal family.</P><P>Lydia was not the only writer in her family; her brother, Joseph Plimsoll Edwards, wrote historical sketches, poems, and pamphlets; and her niece Muriel Katherine Annesley Edwards (1904-1973) was a poet.</P>
           <P>A temperance advocate, Lydia served seventeen years as president of the Truro branch of the Women's Christian Temperence Union. She died of pneumonia one month after her ninetieth birthday, and was buried in Londonderry, NS.</P>
        </AUTHORSUMMARY>
